The New Okinawan Kana are known in their author's documents as simply the â€œOkinawan Kanaâ€ (\cjk{æ²–ç¸„æ–‡å­—}), literally â€œOkinawan lettersâ€. They were originally disseminated in a series of newspaper articles in the RyÅ«kyÅ« ShimpÅ (\cjk{é€±ä¼‘æ–°å ±}) by Funatsu beginning on June 6, 1986.\footnote{Funatsu, Yoshiaki (1986-06-06 â€“ 1986-07-16). \cjk{ã‚ˆã¿ãŒãˆã‚Œåœ°æ–¹èª} [\em{Yomigaere ChihÅgo}; lit. Resurrecting a Regional Language] (series of 15 articles). \em{RyÅ«kyÅ« ShimpÅ} (\cjk{é€±ä¼‘æ–°å ±}). \Href[src=http://www.wwq.jp/q/yomigaere/yomigaere.html]{Archived by Funatsu on his website.}} The name â€œNew Okinawan Kanaâ€ is often used in third party reporting to refer to the characters, as a neutral term for them that does not prescribe their use to the community.\footnote{See e.g.: Emori (1987); Otsuka (2010); Japanese Wikipedia's \Href[src=https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%B2%96%E7%B8%84%E6%96%B9%E8%A8%80%E3%81%AE%E8%A1%A8%E8%A8%98%E4%BD%93%E7%B3%BB]{\cjk{æ²–ç¸„æ–¹è¨€ã®è¡¨è¨˜ä½“ç³»}} [Comparison of Okinawan Scripts] article. While both \cjk{\strong{æ–°ã—ã„}æ²–ç¸„æ–‡å­—} and \cjk{\strong{æ–°}æ²–ç¸„æ–‡å­—} are in use, (having identical English translations, â€œnewâ€), there is a preference for \cjk{æ–°} over \cjk{æ–°ã—ã„}in modern sources.}

Funatsu claims no copyright on these characters and allows free distribution of their shapes and phonetic values, unlike, for example, MojikyÅ; therefore, GlyphWiki, (sticklers for copyright issues,) accept the New Okinawan Kana and have a category for them.\footnote{\Href[src=https://glyphwiki.org/wiki/Group:%e6%b2%96%e7%b8%84%e6%96%87%e5%ad%97]{\cjk{ã‚°ãƒ«ãƒ¼ãƒ—:æ²–ç¸„æ–‡å­—}}. GlyphWiki. Retrieved 2021-09-03.}

There are two repertoirees in current use. The first repertoiree, consisting of all characters up to and including U+1AFE6, is exactly as it was in 1986, as explained in Funatsu's series of articles in the \em{RyÅ«kyÅ« ShimpÅ} (\cjk{é€±ä¼‘æ–°å ±}). The second repertoiree, that plus U+1AFE7â€“U+1AFEA, is of more complex origin. It seems that originally, Funatsu did not consider word origin when coming up with this writing system. However, with the frequent and common mixing of Okinawan and Japanese words, he came up with those four characters in around 2004 to mark out a word's origin. For example, both \Oki{ã¡ã¡} and \Oki{ïª™ã¡} are pronounced equally, as [tÍ¡É•itÍ¡É•i]. However, because \cjk{æœˆ} is pronounced in Japanese as \Oki{ã¤ã}, the second is used: \cjk{\ruby[reading=ïª™ã¡]{æœˆ}}. Likewise, the extremely rare character \Oki{ïªš} has hardly any use at all, being used to transcribe e.g. \Oki{\ruby[reading=ã¿]{ä¸‰}\ruby[reading=ã‹]{æ—¥}\ruby[reading=ïªšã]{æœˆ}}. Nevertheless, just barely enough attestations were found for me to recommend even these rare characters.\footnote{Thanks again to Daichi Shimabukuro.} The chart:

